Trim any fatty bits from the @British chicken thighs{6}. Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a #non-stick pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot add the chicken and cook for around ~{4%minutes} on each side then remove.

> The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile bring @water{900%ml} to the boil in a #kettle{}. Finely chop the @spring onion{4}(finely chopped widthways into ½ cm discs) widthways into ½ cm discs, separate the white from the green parts and peel and finely chop the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and finely chopped). Peel the @ginger{1%knob} using the edge of a #spoon{} and then grate or chop it very finely.

Meanwhile heat @oil{1%tbsp} on medium heat in a #saucepan{} big enough to hold the soup. Add in the whites of the spring onions, the ginger and the garlic. After ~{1%minute} add the @red Thai style paste{2} and stir.

> If you are sensitive to spice add the paste bit by bit to taste.

After another ~{1%minute} add in the @coconut milk{1/2} and stir until smooth. Add the @chicken stock pot{1} with the @water{900%ml} and bring to a simmer.

Add the @peanut butter{1}, the @kaffir lime leaf{1} and @?sugar{1/2%tsp} (if you have some). Roll the @lime{1} firmly between the flat of your hand and the work surface. Once you've loosened it up cut it in half and squeeze half of the lime juice into the laksa. Simmer gently for ~{10%minutes}.

After ~{10%minutes} add the @egg noodle nest{3} and cook for around ~{5%minutes} or until the noodles are soft enough to eat.

Lastly, thinly slice the chicken and add it to the soup. Serve into big #bowls{} with a topping of fresh @coriander{4} and the greens of the spring onions.